== N ==
{{Glossary}}

{{Term|term= Nativism |content= [[Nativism (politics)|Nativism]] }}{{defn|1= an [[opposition to immigration]] that originated in [[Politics of the United States|United States politics]], that distinguishes between Americans who were born in the [[United States]], and "first-generation" immigrants. It is based on fears the immigrants do not share supposedly American values. }}
{{Term|term= Naturalism |content= [[Naturalism (philosophy)|Naturalism]] }}{{defn|1= any of several philosophical stances, typically those descended from [[materialism]] and [[pragmatism]], that do not distinguish the [[supernatural]] (including strange entities like non-natural values, and universals as they are commonly conceived) from [[nature]]. Naturalism does not necessarily claim that phenomena or hypotheses commonly labeled as [[supernatural]] do not exist or are wrong, but insists that all phenomena and hypotheses can be studied by the same methods and therefore anything considered supernatural is either nonexistent, unknowable, or not inherently different from natural phenomena or hypotheses. }}
*{{Term|term= Humanistic naturalism |content= [[Humanistic naturalism]] }}{{defn|1= the belief that human beings, as well as plants and animals, are divine and intricate extensions of nature. Followers share a mutual respect for things created directly by nature, even though life must feed upon life for continuance. While most believers are able to adapt to modern change, naturalists prefer the fair exchange of resources, as was in the case of former agricultural and hunter-gatherer societies. Industry and technology are in exact opposition to naturalism. }}
*{{Term|term= Legal naturalism |content= [[Legal naturalism]] }}{{defn|1= term coined by [[Olufemi Taiwo]] for a current in the social philosophy of [[Karl Marx]] that can be interpreted as one of [[Natural Law]]. Taiwo considered it the manifestation of Natural Law in a [[dialectical materialism|dialectical materialist]] context. }}
*{{Term|term= Metaphysical naturalism |content= [[Metaphysical naturalism]] }}{{defn|1= the [[belief]] that [[nature]] is in fact all that exists. The term applies to any [[world view|worldview]] in which [[nature]] is all there is and all things [[supernatural]] do ''not'' exist (including spirits and souls, non-natural values, and universals as they are commonly conceived). }}
*{{Term|term= Methodological naturalism |content= [[Methodological naturalism]] }}{{defn|1= trying everything possible before saying that a supernatural being/God did it. }}
{{Term|term= Necessitarianism |content= [[Necessitarianism]] }}{{defn|1= a [[metaphysics|metaphysical]] principle that denies that any facts or events are contingent or indeterminate, from human actions to the laws of physics themselves. }}
{{Term|term= Nihilism |content= [[Nihilism]] }}{{defn|1= philosophical view that the world, and especially human existence, is without meaning, purpose, comprehensible truth, or essential value. It is more often a charge leveled against a particular idea than a position to which someone is overtly subscribed. Movements such as [[Dada]], [[Deconstruction]]ism, and [[Punk ideology|punk]] have been described by various observers as "nihilist." }}
{{Term|term= Nominalism |content= [[Nominalism]] }}{{defn|1= the belief that universals or mental concepts have no objective reality but exist only as words or "names" (Latin ''nomina''). }}
{{Term|term= Non-cognitivism |content= [[Non-cognitivism]] }}{{defn|1= the [[meta-ethics|meta-ethical]] view that moral statements do not assert [[proposition]]s i.e. they do not express factual claims or beliefs and therefore lack [[logical value|truth-value]]. This view should be distinguished from [[moral realism]], [[moral skepticism|skepticism]], [[ethical subjectivism|subjectivism]], [[moral relativism|relativism]], and [[moral nihilism|nihilism]]; proponents of these views avow that moral statements are either true or false. }}
{{Term|term= Nontheism |content= [[Nontheism]] }}{{defn|1= the absence of belief in both the existence ''and'' non-existence of a [[deity]] (or [[polytheism|deities]], or other [[numinous]] phenomena). The word is often employed as a blanket term for all belief systems that are not [[theism|theistic]], including [[atheism]] (both [[strong atheism|strong]] and [[weak atheism|weak]]) and [[agnosticism]], as well as certain [[Eastern religion]]s like [[Confucianism]], [[Taoism]], and [[Zen Buddhism]]. }}

{{Glossary end}}{{Compact ToC|side=yes|center=yes|top=yes|symnum=no|seealso=yes|refs=yes|nobreak=yes}}

== O ==
{{Glossary}}
{{Term|term= Objectivism |content= [[Objectivism (Ayn Rand)|Objectivism]] }}{{defn|1= in ethics, the belief that certain acts are objectively right or wrong. }}
{{Term|term= Occasionalism |content= [[Occasionalism]] }}{{defn|1= philosophical theory about [[Causality|causation]] stating that created substances cannot be efficient causes of events. Instead, all events are taken to be caused directly by [[God]] Himself. (A related theory, which has been called 'occasional causation', also denies a link of efficient causation between mundane events, but may differ as to the identity of the true cause that replaces them). }}
{{Term|term= Ontologism |content= [[Ontologism]] }}{{defn|1= ideological system that maintains that God and Divine ideas are the first object of humans' intelligence and that the intuition of God the first act of their intellectual knowledge. Note that [[Martin Heidegger]] used the term ''Onto-theology'', that is answering questions of being with direct reference of belief in God. }}
{{Term|term= Operationalism |content= [[Operationalism]] }}{{defn|1= the philosophy of defining a [[concept]] as the operations that will [[Measurement|measure]] the concept (variables) through specific [[observations]]. }}
{{Term|term= Optimism |content= [[Optimism]] }}{{defn|1= historically, the philosophical position that this is the best of all possible worlds, usually associated with [[Gottfried Leibniz]]. More often used to refer to a cheerful or positive worldview. }}
{{Term|term= Organicism |content= [[Organicism]] }}{{defn|1= philosophical orientation that asserts that reality is best understood as an organic whole. By definition it is close to [[holism]]. [[Benedict Spinoza]] and [[Constantin Brunner]] are two philosophers whose thought is best understood as organicist. }}

{{Glossary end}}{{Compact ToC|side=yes|center=yes|top=yes|symnum=no|seealso=yes|refs=yes|nobreak=yes}}

== P ==
{{Glossary}}

{{Term|term= Pacifism |content= [[Pacifism]] }}{{defn|1= in ethics or politics, an opposition to war or violence. Can range from advocacy of peaceful solutions to problems, to a stance where all violence or force is considered morally wrong. }}
{{Term|term= Pandeism |content= [[Pandeism]] }}{{defn|1= combines [[deism]] (above) with [[pantheism]] (under theism, below) to propose a deistic God that becomes a pantheistic Universe; coined by [[Moritz Lazarus]] and [[Heymann Steinthal]] in ''Zeitschrift für Völkerpsychologie und Sprachwissenschaft'' (1859). }}
{{Term|term= Panentheism |content= [[Panentheism]] }}{{defn|1= ''see its entry under theism, below.'' }}
{{Term|term= Panpsychism |content= [[Panpsychism]] }}{{defn|1= either the view that all parts of matter involve mind, or the more [[holism|holistic]] view that the whole universe is an organism that possesses a mind. It is thus a stronger and more ambitious view than [[hylozoism]], which holds only that all things are alive. This is not to say that panpsychism believes that all matter is alive or even conscious but rather that the constituent parts of matter are composed of some form of mind and are [[Sentience|sentient]]. }}
{{Term|term= Pantheism |content= [[Pantheism]] }}{{defn|1= ''see its entry under theism, below.'' }}
{{Term|term= Particularism |content= [[Epistemological particularism|Particularism]] }}{{defn|1= in the study of knowledge, particularism refers to the approach where one asks the question "What do we know?" ''before'' asking "How do we know?" The term appears in [[Roderick Chisholm]]'s "The [[Problem of the Criterion]]", and in the work of his student, [[Ernest Sosa]] ("The Raft and the Pyramid: Coherence versus Foundations in the Theory of Knowledge"). Particularism is contrasted with [[Methodism (philosophy)|Methodism]], which answers the latter question before the former. Since the question "What do we know" implies that humans retain knowledge, it is fundamentally anti-skeptical. }}
{{Term|term= Pelagianism |content= [[Pelagianism]] }}{{defn|1= the belief that [[original sin]] did not taint [[instinct|human nature]] (which, being created from [[God]], was [[divinity|divine]]), and that mortal [[will (philosophy)|will]] is still capable of choosing [[Goodness and value theory|good]] or [[evil]] without [[Miracle|Divine aid]]. }}
*{{Term|term= Semipelagianism |content= [[Semipelagianism]] }}{{defn|1= a [[Christian]] [[theological]] understanding about [[salvation]], derived from the earlier [[Pelagianism|Pelagian]] teachings about salvation. It teaches that it is necessary for humans to make the first step toward God and then God will complete salvation. }}
{{Term|term= Perfectionism |content= [[Perfectionism (philosophy)|Perfectionism]] }}{{defn|1= an ethical view that maintains an individual lives the Good life to the extent she successfully exercises character traits that are a part of her nature. }}
{{Term|term= Personalism |content= [[Personalism]] }}{{defn|1= school of thought that consists of three main principles: 1) only people are real (in the [[ontological]] sense), 2) only people have value, and 3) only people have [[free will]]. Personalism flourished in the early 20th century at [[Boston University]] in a movement known as Boston Personalism and led by theologian [[Borden Parker Bowne]]. }}
{{Term|term= Perspectivism |content= [[Perspectivism]] }}{{defn|1= philosophical view developed by the [[Germany|German]] [[philosopher]] [[Friedrich Nietzsche]] that all [[perception]] and [[ideation (idea generation)|ideation]] takes place from a particular [[perspective (cognitive)|perspective]] in terms of inner drives as elucidated by the "[[The Will to Power (manuscript)|will to power]]" }}
{{Term|term= Pessimism |content= [[Pessimism]] }}{{defn|1= a belief that the experienced world is the worst possible. It involves a general belief that things are bad, and tend to become worse; or that looks to the eventual triumph of evil over good; it contrasts with optimism, the contrary belief in the goodness and betterment of things generally. A common conundrum illustrates optimism versus pessimism with the question - does one regard a given glass of water as: "Is the glass half empty or half full?" Conventional wisdom expects optimists to reply with half full and pessimists to respond with half empty, but this is not always the case. }}
{{Term|term= Phenomenal conservatism |content= [[Phenomenal conservatism]] }}{{defn|1= a philosophy that holds that it is reasonable to assume that things are as they appear, unless there are positive grounds for doubting this. }}
{{Term|term= Phenomenalism |content= [[Phenomenalism]] }}{{defn|1= in [[epistemology]] and the [[philosophy of perception]], ''phenomenalism'' is the view that physical objects do not exist as things in themselves but only as perceptual [[phenomena]] or sensory stimuli (e.g. redness, hardness, softness, sweetness, etc.) situated in time and in space. In particular, phenomenalism reduces talk about physical objects in the external world to talk about ''bundles of sense-data''. }}
{{Term|term= Philosophy |content= [[Philosophy]] }}{{defn|1= broad field of [[inquiry]] concerning ''[[knowledge]]''; in which the definition of knowledge itself is one of the subjects investigated. Philosophy is the pursuit of [[wisdom]], spans the [[nature]] of the universe and [[human nature]] (of the mind and the body), the relationships between these, and between people. It explores what and how people come to know, including [[existence]] itself, and how that knowledge is reliably and usefully represented, and communicated between and among humans, whether in [[thought]], by [[language]], or with [[mathematics]]. Philosophy is the predecessor and complement of science, and its foundation. It develops notions about the issues that underlie [[science]], and ponders the nature of thought itself. In science, the scientific method, which involves repeated observations of the results of controlled experiments, is an available and highly successful philosophical [[methodology]]. Within fields of study that are concerned directly with humans (economics, psychology, sociology and so forth), in which experimental methodologies are not generally available, subdisciplines of philosophy are developed to provide a rational basis of study in the respective fields. }}
{{Term|term= Physicalism |content= [[Physicalism]] }}{{defn|1= the [[metaphysics|metaphysical]] position asserting that everything that exists has a [[physical properties|physical property]]; that is, that there are no kinds of things other than physical things. In contemporary [[philosophy]] physicalism is most frequently associated with [[philosophy of mind]], in particular the [[dualism (philosophy of mind)|mind/body problem]], in which it holds that the mind is a physical thing in some sense. Physicalism is also called "materialism", but the term "physicalism" is preferable because it has evolved with the physical sciences to incorporate far more sophisticated notions of physicality than matter, for example wave/particle relationships and unseen, non-material forces. }}
{{Term|term= Platonism |content= [[Platonism]] }}{{defn|1= the school of philosophy founded by [[Plato]]. Often used to refer to [[Platonic idealism]], the belief that the entities of the phenomenal world are imperfect reflections of an ideal truth. In metaphysics sometimes used to mean the claim that [[universals]] exist independent of [[particular]]s. Predecessor and precursor of [[Aristotelianism]]. }}
*{{Term|term= Neo-Platonism |content= [[Neo-Platonism]] }}{{defn|1= was a school of [[philosophy]] that took shape in the 3rd century A.D. The school was characterized by a systematization of Platonic metaphysics along with a pursuit of mystical union with the divine. }}
{{Term|term= Pluralism |content= [[Pluralism in philosophy|Pluralism]] }}{{defn|1= in the area of philosophy of the mind, distinguishes a position where one believes there to be ultimately many kinds of substances in the world, as opposed to [[monism]] and [[dualism (philosophy of mind)|dualism]]. (See also cosmotheism). }}
{{Term|term= Polylogism |content= [[Polylogism]] }}{{defn|1= the belief that people who associate with one group or another think differently. }}
{{Term|term= Polytheism |content= [[Polytheism]] }}{{defn|1= the belief in or worship of multiple [[deities]] (usually assembled in a [[Pantheon (gods)|pantheon]]) together with associated [[mythology]] and [[ritual]]s. }}
{{Term|term= Positivism |content= [[Positivism]] }}{{defn|1= philosophical position that the only authentic knowledge is scientific knowledge. It is an approach to the [[philosophy of science]], deriving from Enlightenment thinkers like [[Pierre-Simon Laplace]] (and many others). See also [[logical positivism]]. }}
*{{Term|term= Legal positivism |content= [[Legal positivism]] }}{{defn|1= school of thought in the [[philosophy of law]] that claims that [[law]]s are made (deliberately or unintentionally) by human beings, and that there is no ''inherent'' or ''necessary'' connection between the validity of law and what is [[ethics|ethical]] or [[morality|moral]]. }}
{{Term|term= Postmodernism |content= [[Postmodern philosophy|Postmodernism]] }}{{defn|1= philosophical movement characterized by the [[postmodernism|postmodern]] criticism and analysis of Western [[philosophy]]. Beginning as a critique of [[Continental philosophy]], it was heavily influenced by [[Phenomenology (philosophy)|phenomenology]], [[structuralism]] and [[existentialism]], and by the philosophers [[Friedrich Nietzsche]] and [[Martin Heidegger]]. It was also influenced to some degree by [[Ludwig Wittgenstein]]'s later criticisms of [[analytic philosophy]]. Within postmodern philosophy, there are numerous interrelated fields, including [[deconstruction]] and several fields beginning with the prefix "post-", such as [[post-structuralism]], [[post-Marxism]], and [[post-feminism]]. In particular postmodern philosophy has spawned a huge literature of [[critical theory]]. }}
{{Term|term= Pragmatism |content= [[Pragmatism]] }}{{defn|1= [[philosophy]] that originated in the [[United States]] in the late 19th century. Pragmatism is characterized by the insistence on consequences, utility and practicality as vital components of meaning and truth. Pragmatism objects to the view that human concepts and intellect represent reality, and therefore stands in opposition to both [[Formalism (philosophy)|formalist]] and [[rationalist]] schools of [[philosophy]]. Rather, pragmatism holds that it is only in the struggle of intelligent organisms with the surrounding environment that theories acquire significance, and only with a theory's success in this struggle that it ''becomes'' true. }}
{{Term|term= Prescriptivism |content= [[Prescriptivism (philosophy)|Prescriptivism]] }}{{defn|1= [[Meta-ethics|meta-ethical]] theory about the [[Semantics|semantical]] content of moral statements, introduced by the philosopher [[R. M. Hare]] in his book ''The Language of Morals''. It holds that moral statements functions similarly to [[Moral imperative|imperative]]s. For example, according to prescriptivism, the statement "Killing is wrong" means something like "You shouldn't kill". What it expresses is an ''imperative''. }}
{{Term|term= Probabilism |content= [[Probabilism]] }}{{defn|1= practical doctrine that gives assistance in ordinary matters to one who is skeptical in respect of the possibility of real knowledge: it supposes that though knowledge is impossible, a man may rely on strong beliefs in practical affairs. This view was held by the [[skepticism|skeptics]] of the [[New Academy]] (''see [[skepticism]] and [[Carneades]].''). Opposed to "probabilism" is "probabiliorism" (Latin ''probabilior'', "more likely"), which holds that when there is a preponderance of evidence on one side of a controversy that side is presumably right. [[academic skepticism|Academic skeptics]] accept probabilism, while [[Pyrrhonian skepticism|Pyrrhonian skeptics]] do not. }}
{{Term|term= Psychological egoism |content= [[Psychological egoism]] }}{{defn|1= the descriptive view that humans are always motivated by self-interest. }}
{{Term|term= Psychologism |content= [[Psychologism]] }}{{defn|1= a philosophy that holds that human knowledge can be expanded solely through philosophical study. }}
{{Term|term= Pyrrhonism |content= [[Pyrrhonism]] }}{{defn|1= a sub-philosophy of [[skepticism]] that holds that any assent with regard to non-evident propositions will always remain in a state of perpetual inquiry; therefore, proof or disproof of an observation is not necessarily a valid reason for holding an opinion on the matter. }}
{{Term|term= Pythagoreanism |content= [[Pythagoreanism]] }}{{defn|1= the [[esoteric]] and [[metaphysics|metaphysical]] beliefs held by [[Pythagoras]] and his followers, the Pythagoreans, who were considerably influenced by [[mathematics]]. Pythagoreanism greatly influenced [[Platonism]]. Later revivals of Pythagorean doctrines led to what is now called [[Neopythagoreanism]]. }}

